Movement within Panama is restricted, but for those with tickets, travel to the airport for repatriation is a valid exemption. The British Embassy can facilitate a safe passage letter in Spanish and English for the driver for use at checkpoints to and from the airport. Email us your flight confirmation along with the following details: the driver’s full name; identification number (cedula), licence plate number and make and model of the vehicle, and the names of British nationals traveling with you.
If you are experiencing difficulty in booking transportation, we may be able to assist by putting you in touch with others in the same area who will also be traveling to the capital. The cost of the transport will remain the responsibility of each passenger.
You should arrive in Panama City the day prior to the flight, to prevent any last minute delays. Contact BEPanama.CV@fco.gov.uk if you need information regarding hotels.
Arrival in France
France does not apply quarantine measures to travellers. Nationals of the European Union or certain other countries (UK, Iceland, Liechtenstein, Norway, Andorra, Monaco, Switzerland, San Marino, Holy See) can enter France freely. For third-country nationals, it is mandatory to have your primary residence in the European Union or the above-listed countries and to carry a valid residence permit or long-stay visa.
Flights and trains continue to connect Paris to European capitals. We encourage you to arrange your onward connection to the UK accordingly with the respective rail, road and airline services. See FCO Travel Advice relating to France for further advice.
All travellers must complete an international travel authorisation on the same day of travel to France.
Travellers who have to leave Paris CDG Airport to continue their journey must also complete an authorisation for movement on French territory.
Authorisation forms will also be available at the airport on the day of the flight.
What to do
If you cannot leave Panama at this time, you should:
email your details to BEPanama.CV@fco.gov.uk, so we can alert you when options become available
follow the advice of local authorities, including local measures to help minimise your risk of exposure to coronavirus
find accommodation that’s suitable for your needs
keep in regular contact with family and friends at home, so they know you are safe and well
See more information and advice about staying where you are if you cannot return to the UK.
Future travel options
This travel advice will be updated when departure options become available.
Sign up for travel advice email alerts and follow the British Embassy on Twitter and Facebook.
You will need to pay for your return travel to the UK. If departure options are available but you cannot afford the travel costs and have exhausted all other options for getting funds, you may be eligible to apply for an emergency loan from the government. This is a last resort option and you would need to repay the loan when you are back in the UK. For more information, you should contact Corporate Travel Management (CTM). CTM are a commercial partner of the FCO and are authorised to administer such loans on behalf of the FCO.
Your journey home
The National Travel Health Network and Centre (NaTHNaC) provides advice on how to stay safe as you travel by air. When you arrive back in the UK, follow the guidance for when you return to the UK on steps you should take to protect yourself and others.
Help and support
If you need urgent consular assistance, you can contact the British Embassy on +507 297-6550 or through the recommended consular contacts.
The Embassy cannot provide further information or advice about departure options over the phone. This page will be updated when departure options become available. To get the latest information, sign up for travel advice email alerts and follow the British Embassy on Twitter and Facebook.
